#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:2
msgid "Essential pre-reading for life with LFS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:7
msgid ""
"AUTHOR: Richard A Downing FBCS CITP <TheOldFellow at gmail dot com> DATE: "
"2004-12-28 LICENSE: Creative Commons - Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike "
"2.0 SYNOPSIS: Essential pre-reading for life with LFS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:15
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION: This hint is a list of good documents that you can get\n"
"for free on the Internet, together with some advice from me and my\n"
"friends. It will help you get 'educated' to a level where you can:\n"
" 1. successfully build [1]Linux from Scratch (LFS)\n"
" 2. ask sensible questions on the LFS mailing lists and understand the\n"
" replies.\n"
" 3. stay sane while doing all this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:19
msgid ""
"PREREQUISITES: Just the ability to switch on the computer and access the "
"Internet, navigate to the LFS website and find the hint. The rest is our "
"topic..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:21
msgid "HINT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:35
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Please Note:\n"
"  * This will always be a 'work in progress' and I'm missing a good\n"
" reference on some stuff. So, if you know of, or find a good one,\n"
" please write to me. Also I just like feedback, so it never hurts\n"
" to send an email.\n"
"  * If you are reading a text version, you will find a better\n"
" maintained version of this hint on-line at:\n"
" http://www.109bean.org.uk/lfsdocs/LFS-prereading.html - The URL\n"
" links are easier to follow too.\n"
"  * I generate the text version of this hint by applying lynx -dump to\n"
" the web version. This means that the URL's are collected at the\n"
" end. This isn't so convenient for you, but it is really neat for\n"
" me.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:37
msgid "The LFS book says:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:40
msgid ""
"\"This book assumes that its reader has a good deal of knowledge about using "
"and installing Linux software.\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:44
msgid ""
"The book then suggests some further reading, including this document.  But "
"this is more than just an LFS reading list, we expect you to do some "
"exercises too."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:46
msgid "Part 1. Social stuff. (Most important)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:51
msgid ""
"Many people ask questions badly on the LFS mailing lists. Sometimes they get "
"rude replies. To stay sane, I suggest you read the entertaining [2]How To "
"Ask Questions The Smart Way by Eric Steven Raymond."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:60
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Please note that all the LFS mailing lists expect:\n"
" 1. plain text email. No HTML.\n"
" 2. bottom posting. Add your bit UNDERNEATH the bit you quoted.\n"
" 3. pruned quotes. Don't quote everything, just the significant bit.\n"
" 4. no cross-posts. Just use the right list.\n"
" 5. thick skins. Don't respond to rudeness, just ignore it.\n"
" 6. [3]zazen. (Just Sitting) If others have a flame-war, just sit and\n"
" watch.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:64
msgid ""
"Before asking questions on lfs lists, please search the archives, at least "
"the recent months, and please read [4]The LFS FAQ. Read the latest copy "
"online, not some old thing you downloaded last week."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:68
msgid ""
"If you ask a question that is in the FAQ, you are being extremely rude, not "
"least to the maintainer who does that job out of the goodness of their "
"heart. So you rightly WILL get flamed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:74
msgid ""
"Special note: If someone tells you to RTFM, they are not, repeat NOT, being "
"rude or getting at you. This is the accepted phrase indicating that you need "
"to Read The Friendly Manual. If you have previously been told that a certain "
"Old Low Dutch word is referred to by the 'F', please be assured that this is "
"just a myth :-)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:76
msgid "Part 2. Technical stuff."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:79
msgid ""
"Many people attempt to build LFS without sufficient understanding or "
"experience with LINUX. Here is an excerpt from the tar manual:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:90
msgid ""
"\"You should understand something about how Unix-type operating systems "
"work, and you should know how to use some basic utilities. For example, you "
"should know how to create, list, copy, rename, edit, and delete files and "
"directories; how to change between directories; and how to figure out where "
"you are in the filesystem. You should have some basic understanding of "
"directory structure and how files are named according to which directory "
"they are in. You should understand concepts such as standard output and "
"standard input, what various definitions of the term \"argument\" mean, the "
"differences between relative and absolute path names\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:92
msgid "In the LFS book, it says:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:99
msgid ""
"\"We are going to build the LFS system by using a previously installed Linux "
"distribution such as Debian, SuSE, Slackware, Mandrake, RedHat, etc. We will "
"use the existing Linux system as the development platform, because we need "
"tools like a compiler, linker, text editor, and other development tools to "
"build our system. Get a modern distro and play with it.\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:101
msgid "The Base Distro"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:106
msgid ""
"Choosing a distro is only hard because of the choice, my advice is to choose "
"a cheap one because once you have learned a bit and then built LFS you will "
"junk it. I got mine free with a magazine. However it may help to read [5]The "
"Linux Distribution HOWTO."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:108
msgid "Learning to use UNIX"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:115
msgid ""
"Unlike Windows, Unix requires you to understand what you are doing to get "
"anything much out of it. Both Windows and Unix require deep understanding to "
"get the best out of them. If you are coming from a Windows background or are "
"new to computing in general then reading [6]The UNIX and Internet "
"Fundamentals HOWTO is very basic and will help."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:118
msgid ""
"Also, [7]Linux Installation and Getting Started , yes, is very dated, but is "
"still good and worth a read."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:120
msgid "The Shell"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:127
msgid ""
"If you have read those, then you are aware that we drive Unix though a "
"shell, which provides the command line interface. The shell we use in LFS, "
"as in most of the Linux world, is bash (The Bourne Again Shell).  You need "
"to be fluent in using bash, and [8]The Advanced Bash Scripting Guide is a "
"good tutorial. (Yes, I know it says 'Advanced', but read it anyway, do you "
"want to be a newbie forever?)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:129
msgid "Becoming an apprentice guru"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:133
msgid ""
"Then there are three books that you ought to have available from or on your "
"box for easy reference, skim read them now so you know how to use them:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:135
msgid "[9]The Linux User's Guide"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:137
msgid "[10]The Linux Systems Adminstrator's Guide"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:139
msgid "[11]The Linux Network Administrator's Guide, Second Edition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:142
msgid ""
"I recommend that you put bookmarks to these in your browser, so that you can "
"get to them quickly. It will save lots of time later."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:144
msgid "On Building from Source"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:152
msgid ""
"Having got yourself a LINUX system, and played a bit, you now will know a "
"little about the subject, but before moving on to the building of Linux from "
"Scratch you should learn how to build packages from source code. This is an "
"area where it's hard to find good references.  The LFS book suggests "
"[12]Building and Installing Software Packages for Linux and [13]Autoconf, "
"Automake, and Libtool is good too, if a little advanced."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:155
msgid ""
"It's very important that you have some experience installing a package from "
"source on your distro before attempting LFS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:163
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One good choice would be [14]GNU-Emacs. Here's what to do:\n"
" 1. check out it's homepage\n"
" 2. download a source distribution as a gzipped tar file\n"
" 3. unpack the source with tar and gunzip\n"
" 4. read the README file\n"
" 5. read the INSTALL file\n"
" 6. build it from scratch\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:167
msgid ""
"In doing this you will not only learn how to obtain and build a package from "
"scratch, you'll also prove that you have installed the right tools for your "
"distribution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:172
msgid ""
"If you want a real challenge, try [15]MPlayer. This package is a good test "
"of your developing skills, as you will need to track down and install all "
"it's dependencies first. (You could also cheat and look at the [16]Beyond "
"Linux From Scratch book for a hint.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:176
msgid ""
"IBM, once Big Bad Blue, is now a great supporter of OpenSource and "
"Linux. They have some free tutorials on their [17]developerWorks website."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:184
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Like most Large Multi-nationals, IBM change their site around\n"
"regularly, so any link I give to the tutorials may not be valid any\n"
"more. Follow links to Technical Library and Tutorials though, and you\n"
"should find:\n"
"  * Compiling and installing software from sources\n"
"  * Compiling the Linux kernel\n"
"  * Using regular expressions\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:186
msgid "but there are rich pickings here, even for the experienced."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:188
msgid "Bootstraping"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:192
msgid ""
"One area where even seasoned UNIX veterans seem to have trouble is with "
"setting up the bootstrap for the new LFS system. Often these problems come "
"from not reading the available documents."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:198
msgid ""
"Most people will be building for an X86 platform. Before LFS-5.0 we used "
"Lilo as our recommended BootLoader, from LFS-5.0 we use GRUB.  There is "
"little to choose between the two, and they are not the only choices "
"either. However, it is important to take time to familiarise yourself with "
"the bootloader that you plan to use."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:201
msgid "Check out the homepages for the bootloader (lilo's is not very impressive):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:203
msgid "[18]Grub"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:205
msgid "[19]Lilo"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:207
msgid "And the various HOWTO's, not all will be relevant for you:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:209
msgid "[20]The Lilo mini-HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:211
msgid "[21]Boot + Root + Raid + Lilo : Software Raid mini-HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:213
msgid "[22]Linux+WindowsNT mini-HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:215
msgid "[23]Win95 + WinNT + Linux multiboot using LILO mini-HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:217
msgid "[24]Linux+Win9x+Grub HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:219
msgid "[25]Multiboot with GRUB Mini-HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:223
msgid ""
"If you are building for a non-X86 platform you will have to research your "
"own bootloader, try a google for whatever bootstrap is used by your base "
"distro, but these links may help:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:225
msgid "[26]PA-RISC/Linux Boot HOWTO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:227
msgid "[27]SRM Firmware Howto"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:229
msgid "[28]The Sparc Improved boot LOader"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:235
msgid ""
"But the most important thing you can do is to read the man and info pages "
"for the bootloader. A print (on paper) of the error codes can be very "
"helpful (as the online docs will not be available just when you need this "
"info), and it is vital that you have an alternative means of booting your "
"system before testing your new bootloader."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:237
msgid "Part 3. Other stuff."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:242
msgid ""
"My starting point for any query or gap in my knowledge is google, yours "
"should be too. Go to the [29]Google page, and hit the advanced search "
"button. Learn the full capabilities of this essential tool, spend at least a "
"whole day on this. Truely, you can't live without it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:246
msgid ""
"Note that if US English isn't your native tongue, then google has many "
"national versions. I use [30]Google UK, as I'm English, and find this "
"version more colourful."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:251
msgid ""
"There is a whole heap of documentation at the [31]Linux Documentation "
"Project, some of which I've quoted above. Learn to go there regularly and "
"just poke about, it's a great storehouse of knowledge. Beware though a lot "
"of it is out of date."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:254
msgid ""
"You might want to find some other software for your Linux box. The place to "
"search is: [32]Freshmeat"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:259
msgid ""
"LFS has it's own search system on the website. You can use it to find "
"answers to obscure questions that others have asked in the distant past, as "
"well as 'where is' type inquiries. Look on the LFS website homepage."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/essential_prereading.txt:264
msgid ""
"And finally, whatever you read or don't read concerning LFS, before asking "
"questions, start by reading the FAQ. FAQ stands for 'Frequently Asked "
"Questions'. We don't want to answer them again, so don't ask them. Read "
"[33]The LFS FAQ"
msgstr ""

